&lt;p&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Prerequisite:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
NUC E 302 or NUC E 497A&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Course Objectives:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
Nuclear power industry is carbon-free and reliable base source of electricity.&amp;nbsp; One of the important aspects of nuclear power on which depends the economics and safety of nuclear power plants is the performance of nuclear fuel.&amp;nbsp; During its duty in a reactor core the fuel is subjected to high temperature and radiation conditions.&amp;nbsp; The primary goal of this course is to introduce students to the design of nuclear fuel elements and their behavior in reactor cores along with associated challenges and problems.&amp;nbsp; The major focus will be on fuel designs utilized in LWRs currently in operation or being built (i.e. Generations II, III and II+).&amp;nbsp; Advanced fuels proposed and tested for other reactor types will also be reviewed.&lt;/p&gt;
